Step 6 — Override Files: The Pattern
docker-compose.yml           ← base config (shared across all environments)
docker-compose.override.yml  ← auto-merged in dev (never used in prod)
docker-compose.prod.yml      ← explicit prod overrides
docker-compose.test.yml      ← CI/test overrides

Merge rules:

Lists (like ports, volumes) are concatenated
Maps (like environment) are merged (override wins on conflict)
Scalar values (like image, command) are replaced

Step 7 — Write the Override Files
docker-compose.yml (base — minimal, environment-agnostic):
version: "3.9"

volumes:
  pgdata:

networks:
  app-net:

services:
  db:
    image: postgres:16-alpine
    environment:
      POSTGRES_USER:     ${POSTGRES_USER}
      POSTGRES_PASSWORD: ${POSTGRES_PASSWORD}
      POSTGRES_DB:       ${POSTGRES_DB}
    volumes:
      - pgdata:/var/lib/postgresql/data
    networks:
      - app-net
    healthcheck:
      test: ["CMD-SHELL", "pg_isready -U ${POSTGRES_USER}"]
      interval: 10s
      timeout: 5s
      retries: 5

  app:
    image: myapp:${IMAGE_TAG:-latest}
    environment:
      DB_HOST: db
      DB_USER: ${POSTGRES_USER}
      DB_PASS: ${POSTGRES_PASSWORD}
      DB_NAME: ${POSTGRES_DB}
    networks:
      - app-net
    depends_on:
      db:
        condition: service_healthy
    healthcheck:
      test: ["CMD-SHELL", "wget -qO- http://localhost:3000/health || exit 1"]
      interval: 10s
      timeout: 5s
      retries: 3

docker-compose.override.yml (dev — auto-applied, never commit secrets):
version: "3.9"

services:
  db:
    ports:
      - "5432:5432"             # expose DB to host for local tools (TablePlus, DBeaver)
    environment:
      POSTGRES_PASSWORD: devpassword   # weak password fine locally

  app:
    build:
      context: .
      dockerfile: Dockerfile          # build from source in dev
    image: myapp:dev
    volumes:
      - .:/app                        # live code reload
      - /app/node_modules             # preserve container node_modules
    command: npx nodemon src/index.js # hot-reload dev server
    ports:
      - "3000:3000"
      - "9229:9229"                   # Node.js debugger port
    environment:
      NODE_ENV: development
      DEBUG: "app:*"
    healthcheck:
      disable: true                   # skip healthcheck in dev (faster iteration)

docker-compose.prod.yml (prod — explicit, used with -f flag):
version: "3.9"

services:
  db:
    restart: always
    # no ports — DB NOT exposed to host in production
    environment:
      POSTGRES_PASSWORD: ${POSTGRES_PASSWORD}   # injected by CI/CD secrets

  app:
    restart: always
    image: myregistry/myapp:${IMAGE_TAG}        # pre-built image, no build:
    environment:
      NODE_ENV: production
    deploy:
      resources:
        limits:
          cpus: "0.50"
          memory: 512M
        reservations:
          memory: 256M
    logging:
      driver: json-file
      options:
        max-size: "10m"
        max-file: "5"

  # prod-only: reverse proxy with SSL termination
  proxy:
    image: nginx:alpine
    ports:
      - "80:80"
      - "443:443"
    volumes:
      - ./nginx.conf:/etc/nginx/nginx.conf:ro
      - /etc/letsencrypt:/etc/letsencrypt:ro
    networks:
      - app-net
    depends_on:
      app:
        condition: service_healthy

docker-compose.test.yml (CI — ephemeral, no volumes):
version: "3.9"

services:
  db:
    # no volume — use container layer, wiped after test
    healthcheck:
      interval: 2s     # faster checks in CI
      retries: 10

  app:
    command: npm test
    environment:
      NODE_ENV: test
    depends_on:
      db:
        condition: service_healthy

Step 8 — Run Each Environment
# Dev (auto-merges override.yml)
docker compose up -d

# Preview what the merged config looks like
docker compose config

# Production (explicit file merge)
docker compose -f docker-compose.yml -f docker-compose.prod.yml up -d

# CI/Tests
docker compose -f docker-compose.yml -f docker-compose.test.yml up --abort-on-container-exit

# Verify final resolved YAML for prod
docker compose -f docker-compose.yml -f docker-compose.prod.yml config

Step 9 — Disable/Override a Healthcheck
# Disable inherited healthcheck entirely
healthcheck:
  disable: true

# Override just the interval (keep the test)
healthcheck:
  interval: 30s
  retries: 10

# Check health from CLI without waiting for interval
docker inspect --format='{{.State.Health.Status}}' <container>

# Manually trigger a healthcheck test
docker exec <container> pg_isready -U appuser

Step 10 — COMPOSE_FILE env var (avoid typing -f every time)
# Set once in your shell profile for prod
export COMPOSE_FILE=docker-compose.yml:docker-compose.prod.yml

# Now plain `docker compose up` uses both files
docker compose up -d

# Unset to go back to default
unset COMPOSE_FILE

Interview Questions & Answers
Health Checks
Q1: What are the four states of a Docker healthcheck?

starting — container started, within start_period, no result yet
healthy — last N checks passed
unhealthy — last retries consecutive checks failed
none — no healthcheck defined
Q2: What is start_period and why is it important?

Grace period after container start before failures count toward retries. Critical for slow-starting apps (JVM warmup, DB initialization). Failures during start_period are logged but don't mark the container unhealthy.

Q3: What's wrong with test: ["CMD", "curl", "-f", "http://localhost:3000"]?

curl may not be installed in minimal images (alpine). Use wget -qO- for alpine, or install curl explicitly. Also, the check runs inside the container, so localhost refers to the container, not the host.

Q4: Does an unhealthy container get automatically restarted?

Not by Compose alone — unhealthy just changes the status flag. With restart: on-failure or Swarm/Kubernetes, the orchestrator will act on it. In plain Compose, you need external tooling or a watchdog.

Q5: How do you write a healthcheck directly in a Dockerfile vs Compose?

Dockerfile: HEALTHCHECK --interval=10s --retries=3 CMD curl -f http://localhost/ || exit 1
Compose healthcheck: key overrides the Dockerfile HEALTHCHECK entirely.

depends_on
Q6: What are the three condition values for depends_on?

service_started — dependency container has started (default, no healthcheck needed)
service_healthy — dependency's healthcheck is passing
service_completed_successfully — dependency exited with code 0 (for migrations, init jobs)
Q7: depends_on with service_healthy and my app still crashes on startup. Why?

The healthcheck passes at the DB level (socket is open) but the schema/tables aren't ready yet. Solutions: 1) Run migrations as a separate service_completed_successfully dependency. 2) Add retry/backoff logic in the app itself. depends_on is infrastructure-level, not app-logic-level.

Q8: Can you have a chain of depends_on?

Yes: proxy → app (healthy) → migrator (completed) → db (healthy). Compose resolves the full DAG and starts services in correct order.

Override Files
Q9: What is the difference between -f and --env-file?

-f specifies a Compose YAML file to merge. --env-file specifies a .env-format file for variable substitution inside the YAML. They are independent: -f docker-compose.prod.yml --env-file .env.prod.

Q10: Why should docker-compose.override.yml be in .gitignore?

It often contains developer-specific settings (local paths, weak passwords, debug ports) that differ per machine. Committing it causes merge conflicts and may leak local secrets. Commit a docker-compose.override.yml.example template instead.

Q11: How does list merging work in override files?

Lists like ports and volumes are appended (not replaced). If base has ports: ["3000:3000"] and override adds ports: ["9229:9229"], the result is both ports. For environment (a map), override keys replace base keys with the same name.

Q12: In what order are multiple -f files merged?

Left to right — later files win on conflicts. docker compose -f base.yml -f prod.yml: prod.yml values override base.yml values. The first -f is the base; subsequent files are patches.

Debugging
Q13: How do you debug why a service stays unhealthy?
# See health log with output of each check run
docker inspect <container> \
  --format '{{range .State.Health.Log}}Exit:{{.ExitCode}} Out:{{.Output}}{{"\n"}}{{end}}'

# Run the healthcheck command manually
docker exec <container> pg_isready -U appuser

Q14: How do you temporarily disable a healthcheck without editing the file?

Override in docker-compose.override.yml with healthcheck: { disable: true }, or run a specific service with docker compose run --no-healthcheck app.

